faqs:
  - q: "What is mortgage overpayment?"
    a: "Mortgage overpayment means paying more than your required monthly instalment, with the extra amount applied directly to your loan principal. Reducing the principal faster means less interest accumulates over time, which can shorten your loan term and lower the total cost of borrowing."
  - q: "How does a mortgage overpayment save interest?"
    a: "Extra payments go directly to principal, which reduces the balance interest is charged on. A smaller balance each month means less of every future payment goes to interest and more to principal, compounding the saving over the remaining life of the loan."
  - q: "How does overpaying reduce my mortgage term?"
    a: "When you pay down principal faster, each scheduled payment covers a larger fraction of the remaining balance, and the loan reaches zero ahead of the original schedule. The exact number of years saved depends on your loan amount, interest rate, and how much extra you pay each month — try the calculator to see your specific case."
  - q: "Is it always better to overpay my mortgage?"
    a: "Not necessarily. Whether overpaying makes financial sense depends on your mortgage rate compared to what you might earn on alternative uses of that money, your need for liquidity, and whether your loan carries a prepayment penalty. A guaranteed interest saving may or may not beat an uncertain investment return — model both scenarios before deciding."
  - q: "What is the difference between reducing term vs. reducing monthly payment?"
    a: "By default, extra principal payments shorten the loan term while keeping the monthly payment the same. To reduce the monthly payment instead, you typically need your lender to recast the loan — a process that recalculates payments based on the reduced balance. Not all lenders offer this, and it may carry a fee, so check with your servicer."
  - q: "Are there penalties for overpaying a mortgage?"
    a: "Most modern mortgages have no prepayment penalty, but some older or specialist products cap how much extra you can pay each year without a charge. Check your mortgage documents or ask your servicer before sending a large lump-sum payment."
  - q: "How much should I overpay each month?"
    a: "There is no universal amount — it depends on what you can afford without straining your emergency fund or other financial priorities. Even a modest regular overpayment can meaningfully reduce total interest over a 25- or 30-year term. Use the calculator to model different amounts before committing, and check whether your lender has a maximum annual overpayment allowance."
  - q: "Can I use this calculator for any type of mortgage?"
    a: "This calculator is designed for standard repayment mortgages with a fixed interest rate. Results may be less precise for tracker mortgages, offset mortgages, or interest-only products where the repayment structure differs. Use the output as a planning guide and verify specifics with your lender or a qualified mortgage adviser."
